Full Life-Changing Roadmap – All Phases

Phase 0 – First 3–6 Months – Mindset + Setup + Strong Base (Very Important – Start Here)

1. Super Simple & Powerful Mindset (Read This Every Morning)  
- You are not late — first year is the best time to start  
- No zero days — even 30 minutes daily is big progress  
- Compare only with yourself last month — never with anyone else  
- College exams & internals matter — keep CGPA 7.0+ (below 7.0 hurts many companies)  
- Mistakes are normal — every error is a lesson  
- Small daily work = compound magic (like ₹50 daily saving becomes lakhs in years)  
- Balance is real power: code + college + health + friends + family + rest  
- Your future job = 70% self-learning + 20% projects + 10% college marks  
- You control your future — not college name, not luck, not background  

2. Easy Tracking – Keep It Super Simple  
Use one Google Sheet, Notion page, or even notebook.  
Every week write only these things (takes 5 minutes):  
- Week number  
- How many DSA problems I solved this week  
- What project or coding I did  
- Hours I coded/studied  
- One good thing I did  
- One thing I can improve  
- Energy/mood (1–10)  

Every Sunday spend 10–15 minutes:  
- See what you did last week  
- Re-do 3–5 problems you found hard  
- Plan next 7 days (example: “finish guessing game + 8 easy problems”)  

This small tracking keeps you motivated and shows you are moving forward.

3. Setup Everything (Do in First 10–15 Days)  
- Laptop: Download Python 3.11+ from python.org  
- Editor: VS Code (free, best for beginners) — install Python extension  
- Git: install from git-scm.com  
- Accounts  
  - GitHub (username simple: yourname-aiml)  
  - LinkedIn (headline: "B.Tech CSE AIML '29 | Learning Python & AI/ML")  
  - LeetCode / CodeChef / HackerRank  
  - Kaggle.com (very important for ML datasets & notebooks)  
  - Google account for Drive/Colab  
- Tools  
  - VS Code + Python extension  
  - Google Colab (free GPU for ML later)  
  - Notion or Google Sheet for tracking  

4. Daily Routine Options – Choose One & Stick  
Option 1 – Very Busy College Days (45 min–1.5 hours)  
- 20–40 min Python or DSA practice  
- 15–30 min watch short video  
- 10 min revise or push code  

Option 2 – Normal Days (2–3.5 hours)  
- 50–70 min Python or DSA coding  
- 40–60 min project or ML learning  
- 30–45 min video/notes  
- 15–30 min GitHub/LinkedIn  

Option 3 – Free Days / Weekends (4–6 hours)  
- 1.5 hours DSA/Python practice  
- 1.5 hours project building  
- 1 hour ML intro video  
- 30 min outreach or revision  

5. Health & Balance – Never Skip This  
- Sleep 7–8 hours every night — brain needs rest to learn  
- Walk / play sports / exercise 20–45 minutes daily  
- Drink 2–3 liters water  
- One light day per week (revision + relax only)  
- Eat normal home food — reduce junk  
- Talk to family/friends — don’t sit alone coding all time  
- If tired/stressed — take break, watch movie, sleep extra  

Phase 1 – Absolute Beginner to Early Intermediate (Months 1–9 First Year)

1. Master Python (The Most Important Thing for AI/ML)  
Step-by-Step Learning Order (Do in Order – No Skipping)  
1. Install Python + VS Code (1–2 days)  
2. Hello World, print, input, comments, variables  
3. Data types: int, float, str, bool, None  
4. Operators: + - * / % // ** == != > < and or not  
5. Conditionals: if, else, elif, nested if  
6. Loops: for range, while, break, continue, pass  
7. Lists: create, append/pop/remove, index, slice, loop  
8. Tuples: create, unpack, immutable  
9. Dictionaries: key-value, get, items/keys/values, update  
10. Sets: add/remove, union/intersection/difference  
11. Functions: def, return, default args, *args, **kwargs  
12. Strings: upper/lower, split/join, strip, replace, find  
13. File handling: open/read/write/close txt/csv files  
14. Basic OOP: class, object, __init__, self, methods  
15. Modules: import math, random, datetime, os, sys  
16. Exception handling: try-except-else-finally, raise  
17. List/dict/set comprehension  
18. Lambda functions, map/filter/reduce  
19. Generators (yield basics)  
20. Decorators simple intro  

Resources (Free & Super Easy)  
- CodeWithHarry Python full course (Hindi – clearest for Indian students)  
- Apna College Python playlist (Hindi/English)  
- freeCodeCamp Python for Beginners (English, 4 hours)  
- Automate the Boring Stuff with Python (free online book)  
- W3Schools Python (quick reference + examples)  

Goal after 4–6 months  
- Write 100+ small programs without looking at video  
- Solve problems like calculator, guessing game, pattern print, student manager, file organizer  

2. Easy DSA in Python (Build Logic Step by Step)  
Platforms (Free & Easy)  
- CodeChef Starters contests (best for beginners)  
- LeetCode easy section  
- GeeksforGeeks beginner practice  
- HackerRank Python domain  

First 9 Months Topics (Only Easy to Medium)  
Months 1–3 (Easy)  
- Pattern printing (stars, numbers, alphabet, diamond, pyramid)  
- Basic math (prime check, factorial, GCD, LCM, sum of digits, reverse number)  
- Arrays/lists (sum, max/min, second max, reverse, rotate left/right, remove duplicates)  
- Strings (palindrome, count vowels/consonants, reverse words, anagram check, substring search)  
- Simple recursion (factorial, fibonacci, sum of digits, power)  

Months 4–6 (Easy-Medium)  
- Searching: linear search, binary search basics  
- Sorting: bubble sort, selection sort, insertion sort intro  
- Two pointers easy (sum pair, remove duplicates from sorted)  
- Hashing basics (use dict for frequency count)  

Months 7–9 (Medium Intro)  
- Sliding window simple (max sum subarray of size k)  
- Linked list basics (reverse, cycle detection, middle)  
- Stack/queue simple (valid parentheses, next greater element)  

Target: 400–700 total problems  
- 250–450 easy  
- 150–250 medium  
Do 5–10 problems per week — think first, don’t copy  

3. First Python Projects (Build Confidence & Resume)  
Do 10–15 small projects in first year — these make you believe in yourself.

Project Ideas (Easy to Medium – Do Them in Order)  
1. Number Guessing Game (computer thinks number, you guess, hints)  
2. To-Do List Manager (add, delete, show, mark done, save to file)  
3. Quiz Game (10–20 MCQ, score, timer, categories)  
4. Student Marks System (add student, show marks, average, topper, save file)  
5. Simple Calculator (add, subtract, multiply, divide, power, square root)  
6. Password Generator (random strong passwords with options)  
7. Rock Paper Scissors Game (play with computer, score board)  
8. Currency Converter (hardcode 5–10 currencies, real-time API later)  
9. File Organizer (sort files in folder by type: images, docs, videos)  
10. Expense Tracker (add expense, category, show monthly total)  
11. Weather Checker (use free API like openweathermap)  
12. Simple Chatbot (rule-based replies)  
13. BMI Calculator with advice  
14. Age Calculator (from birth date)  
15. Tic Tac Toe Game (console version)  

Rule  
- Finish one project every 3–5 weeks  
- Put every project on GitHub  
- Make simple README: name, what it does, how to run, screenshots  
- Bonus: add comments in code explaining each part  

4. Start AI/ML Basics (No Math Pressure Yet – Just Understand)  
Goal: Know what AI/ML is — no deep coding yet.

What to Learn (Very Easy)  
- What is AI? (machines doing smart things like humans – Siri, ChatGPT)  
- What is Machine Learning? (computer learns from data/examples instead of hard rules)  
- Types of ML: supervised (with correct answers), unsupervised (find patterns), reinforcement (learn by reward)  
- What is data? (numbers in table, text, images, videos)  
- Simple libraries intro: numpy (fast math arrays), pandas (data tables like Excel)  

Resources (Free & Super Simple)  
- Apna College AI/ML intro playlist (Hindi – clearest)  
- CodeWithHarry Machine Learning intro (Hindi)  
- 3Blue1Brown Neural Network series (English – beautiful animation videos)  
- Kaggle Intro to Machine Learning course (free, 4 hours, very simple)  

Goal  
- Understand: ML = computer finds patterns in data to make predictions  
- Know difference: AI > Machine Learning > Deep Learning  

Phase 2 – Early Intermediate to Strong Intermediate (Months 7–18 – End First Year to Mid Second Year)

1. DSA – Move to Medium Comfortably  
Monthly Topics  
Months 7–9  
- Advanced arrays: Kadane algorithm (max subarray sum), sliding window, two pointers  
- Binary search medium problems (rotated array, peak element)  
- Linked list basics (reverse, cycle detection, middle, remove nth)  
- Stack & Queue simple (next greater element, valid parentheses, min stack)  

Months 10–12  
- Recursion medium (subsets, permutations easy, combination sum)  
- Trees basics (traversal pre/in/post/level, height, diameter intro)  
- Graphs intro (BFS/DFS on grid, number of islands simple)  

Months 13–18  
- Greedy medium (jump game, activity selection)  
- DP 1D intro (fibonacci, climbing stairs, house robber)  
- Company medium problems (Amazon, Flipkart, Microsoft tagged easy-medium)  

Target: 600–900 total problems  
- 400–600 medium  
- 80–150 hard (only if you enjoy)  

Resources  
- Striver SDE Sheet (medium focus)  
- Love Babbar 450  
- takeUforward YouTube (medium series)  
- LeetCode explore cards  

Rule: Solve 6–10 problems per week. Focus on understanding pattern — not speed.

2. Python for AI/ML – Become Really Strong  
- Numpy full: indexing, slicing, broadcasting, linear algebra basics  
- Pandas full: read CSV/Excel, clean missing values, groupby, merge/join, pivot tables  
- Matplotlib/Seaborn: line/bar/scatter plots, histograms, boxplots, pairplot, heatmaps  
- Scikit-learn intermediate: preprocessing (scaling, encoding), pipelines, cross-validation  

Resources  
- Kaggle Python course (free, hands-on)  
- Kaggle Pandas course  
- CampusX YouTube ML playlist (Hindi, very clear)  
- freeCodeCamp Data Analysis with Python  

Practice  
- Download 8–12 Kaggle datasets  
- Clean & explore each one  
- Make 10+ different visualizations per dataset  
- Do simple analysis (average by group, correlation, outliers)  

3. Machine Learning – Hands-On Intermediate  
Topics  
- Feature engineering (scaling, encoding categorical, handling missing, feature selection)  
- Model selection & comparison (which model for which problem)  
- Ensemble basics (Random Forest, Voting, stacking intro)  
- Hyperparameter tuning intro (GridSearch, RandomizedSearch)  
- Imbalanced data basics (SMOTE, class weight)  

Projects (Do 8–14 – These Make Resume Strong)  
1. House price prediction (advanced features + tuning)  
2. Titanic survival (ensemble + feature engineering)  
3. Customer churn prediction (imbalanced data)  
4. Credit card fraud detection (high imbalance)  
5. Wine quality prediction (regression + classification)  
6. Heart disease prediction (multiple models)  
7. Diabetes prediction (tuning + comparison)  
8. Sales forecasting (time series simple)  
9. Customer segmentation (K-means + visualization)  
10. Sentiment analysis on reviews (text)  
11. Fake news detector  
12. Loan approval prediction  

Goal for Each Project  
- Load & explore data  
- Clean & engineer features  
- Train 3–5 models  
- Compare results (accuracy/F1/AUC)  
- Make notebook clean & beautiful  
- Deploy simple web app with Streamlit  

